{ Author's Preface to the Second Edition  The French Rubinstein is while regularly played by grandmasters and well respected amongst them as a tough nut to crack far from being a mainstream opening.  I was somewhat surprised about the success and rather quick selling-out of the first edition of this book. It looks like there is great interest in a solid reply to 1. e4, one which is easy to learn and not that theoretical !  The project updating the material and analyzing what has happened in the last four years turned out to be an exciting one. Germany's Georg Meier  (currently rated 2648)  continues to be the main hero of this opening, testing it regularly against even the very best players in the world and generally representing the black side very well.  I was especially fascinated by the new concept he introduced last year in one of the absolute main lines of the Rubinstein in his game against Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, reaching a very comfortable draw against the 2800-player from France  (see chapter 6 for details)  .  Naturally, four years of tournament praxis in over-the-board and correspondence play and the analysis of all the material with the latest engines have led to several different evaluations and new directions.  Without a doubt, there are dangerous lines for Black to face, but the French Rubinstein remains solid as a rock, and is certainly an opening which is here to stay.  As in the first edition, the second part of the book provides a repertoire against Whites alternatives to the main moves 3. Nc3 and 3. Nd2. In that part, one of the major changes of direction took place in my recommended set-up against the French Advance 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Bd7 5. Nf3 a6.  This set-up had temporarily been put under a cloud by a correspondence game in the main line 6. Bd3 cxd4 ?! 7. cxd4 Bb5 8. Bc2 !. However, I have realized that players with Black, like Russian GM Vyacheslav Ikonnikov, have recently gone a different direction by choosing the move 6... Nc6 !, which puts early pressure on d4 often combined with ...Qb6 and is a very viable option.  You can find all the details about this exciting line in chapter 10. This chapter should be of special interest for Sicilian O'Kelly players as well, as the move order 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6 3. c3 e6 4. d4 d5 5. e5 Bd7 not only transposes to our French line, but also is one of the main tabiyas of the O'Kelly System !  The new edition of this book is also an extended one, with 17 new main games and overall significantly more material, while still trying to keep the necessary theoretical knowledge to play the repertoire within reasonable bounds.  Last, but not least, I wish to thank my wife Liudmyla for taking care of our children so many times, and thus patiently giving me all those hours to finish the project.  Dear chess friend, I wish you much fun and success playing the Rubinstein Defense !  Hannes Langrock, Leipzig, March 2018 }
