1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Bd3 Be7
{ Generally we want to play ...c7-c5 quickly in the Rubinstein if we have the chance to do so without incurring a disadvantage. Thus,   6...c5 !  is the recommended move  (see also Chapter 6 of this book)  . Then, if White exchanges with  7.Nxf6+  Nxf6  8.dxc5  Bxc5  we have moved our bishop only once  (... Bf8-xc5)  and thus saved a tempo compared with the slower ...Bf8-e7 followed by a later ...Be7xc5. But again, it is easy to criticize Rubinsteins little inaccuracy, knowing the theory which developed over a hundred years and thousands of games. }
7. O-O Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Nf6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. c3 b6
{ In the last game, Rubinstein had developed his bishop to d7. Five days later he chooses b7, which today is the most typical place for Blacks bishop in the Rubinstein Variation ! }
11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Ne5 Qd5 13. f3 c5
{ Rubinstein chooses a very good moment for this typical advance, right after provoking White to weaken the g1-a7 diagonal. }
14. Be3 cxd4 15. Bxd4 Bc5 16. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 17. Kh1 Rad8
{ Black is very comfortable, but nothing serious has happened yet. The next part of the game Wolf plays poorly. }
18. Rfe1 Rd6
{ Doubling rooks on the d-file is a typical plan for Black in this type of position. }
19. Qc2
{ It is not clear what the queen is doing here.  White needs the c2-square for his bishop to seek simplifications with   19.Rad1  Rfd8  20.Bc2 }
19... Rfd8 20. Rad1 g6 21. Nc4 R6d7 22. Ne5 Rd5 23. b4
{ This only weakens Whites queenside structure. } 23... Qc7 24. Nc4 Ba6
{ Turning the attention to the kingside with   24...Rh5 !  would have won quickly. One sample line is  25.h3  Rxh3+  26.gxh3  Bxf3+  27.Kg1  Qg3+  28.Kf1  Qxh3+  29.Kg1  Ng4  and Black mates. }
25. Nb2 Bxd3 26. Rxd3 Rxd3 27. Nxd3
{ Black has a clear positional advantage, but now he goes for a repetition of moves. The reason is simple: It was the last round of the tournament and Rubinstein only needed a draw to secure clear first place. }
27... Qc4 28. Ne5 Qc7 29. Nd3 Qc4 30. Ne5 Qc7 31. Nd3 Qc4 *

