5... Ngf6 6. Bd3 c5 7. Nf3
{ Whites early c2-c3 has some points, one being that the bishop can slide back to c2 in case Black exchanges on e4 followed by ...Nf6. So far there are only a small number of grandmaster games in this line  (one of the first being the 2700+ clash Kramnik-Bareev though !)  , but I expect it to become more popular in the future. }
7... Nxe4
{ Meier allows the mentioned idea, but his chosen sequence still looks most principled.  Another long-time Rubinstein expert, Swiss grandmaster Yannick Pelletier, played   7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Be7  against GM A.Zhigalko  (Bilbao 2014)  . }
8. Bxe4 Nf6 9. Bc2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc5 11. O-O
{ The most dangerous continuation. White is ready to play with an isolated pawn and hopes to create attacking chances.   11.Ba4+  Bd7  12.Bg5  Bxa4  13.Qxa4+  Qd7  14.Qxd7+  Nxd7  was equal in the aforementioned game Kramnik-Bareev, Monte Carlo rapid 2004. It is worth playing though that game in your database. Bareev managed to take over the initiative in the ending and to outplay his world-class opponent.   11.Be3  O-O  12.Nxe6  This tactical shot does not lead to an advantage for White.  Qxd1+  13.Bxd1   13.Rxd1  Bxe3  14.Nxf8  Bb6 !   xd8  15.Nxh7  Nxh7  is similar  13...Bxe3  14.Nxf8  Bc5  15.Nxh7  Kxh7  and Blacks two pieces were not worse than Whites rook and two pawns, Moisa-Merrell, corr 2013. }
11... Bxd4 12. cxd4
{ 12.Ba4+  was tried in a recent grandmaster game.  Bd7  13.Qxd4  Bxa4  14.Qxa4+  Qd7  15.Qh4  O-O  16.Bg5  Nd5  17.c4  f6  18.cxd5  fxg5  19.dxe6  gxh4  20.exd7  Rad8  21.Rad1  Rf7  22.Rd4  Rfxd7  23.Rxh4  Yes, we have only played 23 moves ! Despite being deep in the endgame, this still looks relevant from an opening point of view because of the forced character of the moves following 16... Nd5.  Rd4  Black decides to exchange one rook, and with the other one getting to d2 this looks like a technical draw.  24.Rxd4  Rxd4  25.Rb1  b5  26.Kf1  Rd2  27.a3  a5  28.b4  axb4  29.Rxb4  Rd3  30.Rxb5  Rxa3  and Black had no trouble defending the remaining 2-3 on one wing in Macieja-Nyzhnyk, Chicago 2016. }
12... Bd7
{ We have seen this type of position before in this book. Usually Whites bishop pair and attacking potential compensate for the isolated pawn, but not more than that if Black is careful. }
13. a4
{ A strong novelty and most likely a result of home preparation. The idea is to bring the rook into the attack via a3. Previously played more standard approaches pose less problems:   13.Bf4  Rc8  14.Re1  O-O  15.Be5  Bc6  16.Qd3   16.Re3  g6  17.Rh3  (Martin Del Campo-Hadjiyiannis, Manila 1992)  and again I like the annoying  Qd5 !  White has to make some move which he does not really like   18. f3;  18.Rg3  and Black can continue with 18... Nd7 and a fine position.  16...g6  17.Rac1  and now the immediate  Nd7  as played in Helmreich-Borisovs, corr 2011, looks fine  while I have also looked at first activating the queen with   17...Qd5 !?   xg2  . There is one tactical option for White:  18.Qh3  Nd7  19.Bb3  Qb5  20.Bxe6  which however seems to peter out in equality.  Nxe5  21.Bxc8   21.Rxe5  Qxb2  22.Bxf7+  Kg7  23.Rf1  Rc7  24.Bb3  Qxd4 =  21...Nd3  22.a4  Qd5  23.Rxc6  Qxd4  24.Qe3  Qxe3  25.Rxe3  bxc6  26.Rxd3  Rxc8  with a drawn rook endgame.   13.Re1  Bc6  14.Bf4  O-O  15.Qd3  Qd5 !  16.f3  This move kills all of Whites attacking ideas on the third rank. In Stephenson-Dorn, corr 2013, Black now could have played  Qb5  offering a favorable exchange of queens. White can avoid this with  17.Qd2  but  Nd5  is equal.   17...Qxb2 ??  18.Bxh7+   13.Bg5  Bc6  14.Ba4  Bxa4  15.Qxa4+  Qd7  16.Qa3  was tried twice by the same correspondence player with White. But the problem is that after  Nd5  Black has the easy plan of finishing development with ...f6 and ...Kf7. Black already had a positional advantage in Popov-Rangel Garcia, corr 2015. }
