31. Qxe6+
{ Now in contrast White could have still tried   31.Bxb7+  Kxb7  32.Rxh7+  += }
31... Qd7 32. Bxb7+ Kxb7
{ - A tense game with a correct result, which incidentally brought Georg Meier a victory of a strong closed GM tournament in St. Louis. At some points in the game the engine evaluates the position as r, although it is hard to say if it overestimates Whites activity or if there really is something. Future games and analysis will show, how this new line is to be evaluated. It seems likely that there are potential improvements for both sides after 13. a4. Summary In the last chapter of the Rubinstein section we have looked at less commonly played lines, which I thought are relevant enough to be covered in the book. In the variation 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Qe2 c5 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. O-O Nxe4 9. Bxe4 Nc5 10. Rd1, White relies on his activity and a small lead in development. However, by giving up the bishop pair, he pays a price for that. After 10... Be7 11. Nxd4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 O-O Black is solid enough as the game Balogh-Laznicka showed. The line 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Bd3 c5 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6 8. Be3 has been played by a number of grandmasters and is actually not a sideline with more than 400 games according to my database. I do like Pelletiers treatment, 8... Qc7 9. Qe2 a6 10. O-O b6 !?, which gave him a fairly comfortable draw against the significantly higher-rated Fabiano Caruana. The game Korneev-Morozevich analyzed the position after 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bd3 c5 8. O-O cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 and in particular other moves than 10. Nf3  (which would transpose to Chapter 1)  . These moves are not dangerous for Black at all. For example, Morozevich quickly equalized following 10. Be3 Bb6 11. c3 e5. Finally, the game Li-Meier takes a look at the variation 5. c3 !? Ngf6 6. Bd3 c5 7. Nf3. The early c2-c3 frees the c2square for the bishop. Meier played the principled 7... Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Nf6 9. Bc2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc5 and as usual held his own. But this line is still quite fresh and unexplored, and there will surely be more developments in the coming years. }
