{ Chapter 10 French Advance 4. c3 } 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3
{ The advance variation is the most important alternative to the main moves 3. Nc3 and 3. Nd2. Many grandmasters play it regularly, among them worldclass player Alexander Grischuk. White immediately gains space in the center and based on that space advantage, White has won a lot of nice attacking games. Of course, there are also downsides, the most obvious positional drawback being that after a future ...c5xd4/c3xd4, White has a backward pawn on d4 and there are many instances of White eventually losing that pawn and the game. The system I am recommending for Black is quite rare, but I believe it is sound and it has brought me good results since 2003. }
4... Bd7 5. Nf3 a6
{ It also is a pragmatic choice, avoiding a lot of theory compared with the main lines against the French Advance, which is especially significant for those, who plan to pick up the Rubinstein as a second or third weapon against 1. e4 and otherwise do not play the French. If you instead go for one of the main set-ups against the Advance like 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 or 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7, you can easily have more theory to study than in the whole Rubinstein complex, which is our weapon against 3. Nc3 and 3. Nd2 ! I first came across this variation in an opening seminar given by Matthias Wahls, a well-known grandmaster from Hamburg, who later switched from chess to poker. Interestingly, that seminar was not about the French, it was about the OKelly Sicilian: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6. Wahls recommended meeting the move 3. c3 !? with 3...e6 ! 4. d4 d5 5. e5 Bd7, reaching the exact position as on the above diagram ! In fact, this position arises more often via the OKelly than via the French Advance move order. While it definitely is a sideline, it is also true that a good number of masters and grandmasters have already played this variation with the black pieces. A grandmaster who uses it regularly is Serbia's Sinisa Drazic. With 5... a6, Black has played a seemingly slow move. However, in combination with ...Bd7, there is a simple and sound strategic idea, well-demonstrated in the line }
6. Be2
{ So, if Blacks idea is to take on d4 and after c3xd4 play Bb5 to exchange bishops, what should White do against this ? The way this question was asked, the reply   6.a4 ?!  suggests itself.  With this move, White takes the b5-square under control and thus prevents Blacks idea. However, it does not contribute to the development of Whites forces and leads to a weakening of the b4-square. The drawbacks predominate here and, starting with  6...Nc6  Black gets a good game by playing natural moves. 6. a4 ?! is investigated in the game IvekovicSulava  (game 42)  , which also takes a look at 6.a3, 6.Na3 and 6.h4.  Of these moves,   6.a3  deserves some special attention, as after this Black should refrain from the ...cxd4/...Bb5 idea for concrete reasons. Instead, Sulavas  6...c4 !  a standard answer to a2-a3 in this sort of structure is the correct way to proceed. This is a good moment to mention one thing which I learned in the process of deeply studying Blacks set-up for several times: While the idea to exchange on d4 followed by ...Bb5 after c3xd4 is an important and recurring motif, it is not always the right way to play. We cannot play on autopilot and should be flexible, depending on which line White chooses.  Another attempt is   6.dxc5  Bxc5  7.Bd3  Whites reasoning is that he can successfully apply a blockading strategy after Black has played the somewhat slow moves 4... Bd7 and 5... a6. White would like to follow up with O-O, Bf4, Nbd2-b3-d4 and then control the position on the dark squares. However, in reality, Black has more than one good answer. Interesting is  Ne7 !?  which delays the development of the b8-knight and thus retains the option to play ... Bb5, for example, after  Instead, in our game featuring 6. dxc5, Tomczak-Kurmann  (game 43)  , Black played the direct   7...Nc6  8.O-O  f6 !  which is also convincing.  8.Bf4  Ng6  9.Bg3  A serious test of Blacks set-up are lines in which, after ...cxd4, White recaptures on d4 with the knight, intending to control the central d4-square with a piece. In particular, I am referring to the line   6.Nbd2  cxd4  7.Nxd4  However, Black gets enough counterplay in the center by playing ...Nc6, possibly prepared by ...Nge7, to be able to recapture on c6 with the knight. In our game Schlosser-Braun  (game 44)  , Black not only equalizes, he even manages to grab the initiative with an ambitious pawn sacrifice and then score a nice victory.   6.Be3  is the third most popular move after 5... a6. It has the disadvantage of leaving b2 unprotected though, which Black can make use of by playing  cxd4  7.cxd4  Qb6 !  Instead, in Popilsky-Soffer  (game 45)  , the grandmaster from Israel did chose the standard   7...Bb5  and also did well, although this might be less accurate.  The most frequent move is   6.Bd3  and this is also one of the critical tests of Blacks set-up.  Here we have a case, in which the standard recipe does not work well, as in the line  cxd4 ?!  Instead, the move   6...Nc6  is critical, which starts to put pressure on d4 and has been played by several grandmasters in the last years.  7.O-O  is mostly played, but after  An important alternative is   7.a3  covering the b4-square and potentially preparing b2-b4, which is analyzed in the game PonkratovAkselrod  (game 47)  , which saw Black create counterplay in typical French fashion after  Qb6  8.Bc2  Rc8  9.O-O  cxd4  10.cxd4  g5 !  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  Qb6  White already has some issues to protect d4 in a convenient way as  9.Bc2  Nb4 !  leads to a favorable piece exchange for Black after, for instance,  10.Bb3  Bb5  11.Re1  Nd3  White has tried several moves after 8... Qb6, but there is no advantage as the game Kooijmans-Ikonnikov  (game 46)  shows.  7.cxd4  Bb5  8.Bc2 !  recent developments have been in Whites favor. }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb5
{ Black is about to achieve a desirable strategic goal: the exchange of his problematic light-square bishop. }
8. Bxb5+ axb5
{ Black had to allow the doubling of his b-pawn, but it is not even clear if that is a disadvantage. Black will soon move the pawn to b4, gaining space and also fixing a2 as a weakness. As tournament praxis has shown, he should not have any problems here, and in general not after the tame 6. Be2. However, 6. Be2 is frequently seen especially on amateur level and the game Tomazini-Drazic  (game 41)  takes a close look at it. }
