{ Chapter 11 French Advance: White Does Not Play 4. c3 The three lines that we will investigate in this chapter 4. Nf3, 4. Qg4 and 4. dxc5 are quite old, and it is worth mentioning that all three of them were played by Aron Nimzowitsch  (1886-1935)  . This implies that there must be a serious concept behind these moves and even if these lines are not very popular today you can get crushed by them easily if you are caught by surprise and do not know how to meet them. However, as we will see, if Black knows what he is doing, it turns out to be White who can get into trouble quickly. The philosophy behind these three moves is similar: White passes on the idea of maintaining a pawn on d4, and instead, he focuses on bolstering the e5-pawn with pieces, and at the same time he looks for attacking chances on the kingside. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3
{ is the most popular of these three moves.  After } 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ would be comfortable for Black } *

