 Nxd3  13.Nb5  Nxf4  14.Nxc7+  Bxc7  15.g3  Nh3+ !  16.Kg2  e5  17.Qxd5  O-O  ∓  and Black's three pieces were much stronger than Whites queen in Lam-Geerken, corr 2014.  12...Bxe5  13.Bb5+ ?   13.Qh5  Bf6  14.Qxd5  O-O  15.Qe4  g6  16.Nxd4  Qb6  with a double attack against d4 and b2 is also bad for White.  13...Kf8  14.Qh5  Bf6  15.Qxd5  a6  16.Ba4  g6  -+  Schmidt- D.Meier, Kiel 2003.   9.Bxg6 !  The only way to keep a balanced game. Now both recaptures make sense.  fxg6   9...hxg6  10.Nb3  White will regain his pawn with roughly equal chances. One example on master level went  Bd7  11.Nbxd4  Nxd4  12.Nxd4  Be7  13.Bf4  f5  14.Qd2  Rh5 !  Black has to push ...g6-g5 in order not to get dominated on the dark squares.  15.Nf3  Qd8  16.Be3  g5  17.h3  Kf7  18.c4  g4  →  and Black had taken over the initiative in Crosa Coll-Cubas, Sao Jose de Rio Preto 2003.  10.Nb3  Be7  11.Bf4   11.Nbxd4  Nxd4  12.Nxd4  O-O  13.Qg4  Bd7 =  Freeman-Hague, West Bromwich 2003  11...O-O  12.Bg3  Bd7  13.Nfxd4  Nxd4  14.Nxd4  Qb6  15.Re3  Rac8  16.Rb3  Qa6  17.Rd3  g5  18.Rd2  Be8  19.f3  g4 !?  A beautiful idea by Uhlmann. After White accepts the pawn sacrifice, Blacks bishop will get a nice outpost on e4.  20.fxg4  Bg5  21.Re2  Bg6  22.h4  Be7  =∞  23.Qd2  Bc5  24.Rf2  Bxd4  25.Qxd4  Rxf2  26.Bxf2  b6  27.c3  Qe2  28.b3  Rf8  29.Re1  Qxa2  ∓  Skrobek-Uhlmann, Warsaw 1983.  9...Nf4  For   7.a3  Ng6  8.Re1  see 7. Re1 Ng6 8. a3. }
