{ Actually, this is not a sacrifice, as Black immediately gets two pawns and a bishop for the rook.  Many roads lead to Rome in this position. Black played   23...Ne5  which is strong, and he eventually won after mistakes by both sides.   23...Bxg3 !  24.Qxg3  e5  -+  is massive for Black and probably the clearest way to victory. }
24. gxh3 Qxh3+ 25. Kg1 Bxg3 26. Qh5 { 26.Qg2  Qh4  is also hopeless. } 26...
Qxh5 27. Bxh5 e5
{ Blacks pawns are about to start rolling. This, in combination with the bishop pair and the weakness of Whites gpawn, means that Black is totally winning despite not having a material advantage yet. }
