{ Giving up a center pawn like this looks illogical, but in the old days this move had been played by legends like Keres, Nimzowitsch and Tarrasch. In a few words, John Watson explains the concept behind this line: Rather than defend d4, White shifts his attention to bolstering e5 with pieces, so that after ...f6, he will be able to occupy the outpost on e5. The problem for White is that this concept fails, because if Black plays accurately, White will not be able to keep the crucial e5-square under control. Furthermore, it is worth noting that as Simon Williams points out in Attacking Chess: The French the position after 4. dxc5 can also arise from a Caro Kann after the moves 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 e6, where it is Whites move. According to Williams, that Caro Kann line is known to be OK for Black; therefore it is no surprise that with an extra tempo Black already has good chances to gain the advantage ! }
