1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. f3 Bb4 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ Via transposition, we have reached the Winckelmann-Reimer-Gambit, which usually arises after the moves 3... Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 dxe4 6. f3 ?. }
6... e5
{ There might be other good options, but I like this move a lot. By giving back the pawn  (an offer, which White usually does not accept)  , Black tries to take over the initiative himself. With ...e6-e5, Black fights for the center and, as Watson points out, also frees the c8bishop. As we will see, White often later suffers from his bad pawn structure especially if at some point he decides to capture on e5. Objectively speaking, I do not think that there is a way for White to equalize. }
7. Be3
{ The most popular continuation. It seems that White has tried almost every legal move in this position, I would like to take a look at some of them:  Blacks last move allows White to immediately win back the pawn with   7.dxe5  but this is almost never played as after  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  Bf5  White lands in an uncomfortable ending with the inferior pawn structure. It is already clear that White will have to fight hard for a draw after 8 moves !  As usual   7.fxe4 ?  runs into  Qh4+   7.Bc4  is well met by  Nc6  8.d5  Na5  9.Ba2  Nf6  as given by Watson. Black is clearly better here and also has other promising options like   9...Qh4+  10.g3  Qh5  or   9...b6  (idea ...Ba6)  10.Qe2  Qh4+  11.g3  Qh5   7.Bb5+  c6  8.Bc4  is an attempt to improve over 7. Bc4, as Black now cannot develop his knight to c6. However, d7 is also not a terrible square for the knight, and after  Bf5  Black is better.  9.fxe4  Here is an example of how quickly White can go downhill in the 6... e5 line in over-the-board play:   9.Be3 ?!  Nd7  10.Qe2  Qa5  ∓  11.Bd2  Ngf6  12.Bb3  O-O  13.h4  exf3  14.Nxf3  e4  15.Ne5  Nxe5  16.dxe5  Qxe5  -+  Feicht-Hein, Gladenbach 2011  9...Qh4+  10.Kf1  Bxe4  11.dxe5   11.Qe2  Nd7  12.dxe5  Nxe5  13.Nf3  Bxf3  14.Qxe5+  Ne7  15.Bd3  and now in Grott-Leisebein, corr 1999, Blacks best would have been  f6  16.Qe3  Bd5  17.Rb1  Qg4  ∓  with a sound extra pawn and good winning chances.  11...Bxg2+  12.Kxg2  Qxc4  13.Rb1  Whites pawn structure is an absolute disaster and he is a pawn down. Surprisingly, he is still in the game. It is not enough to equalize though, for example,  b6  14.Rb4  Qd5+  15.Qxd5   15.Nf3  Qxd1  16.Rxd1  Ne7  17.e6  f6 !  18.Rbd4  Na6  ∓  The e6-pawn is slightly annoying, but also a potential target, which can be attacked by Blacks knight and after short castling rook.  15...cxd5  16.Rg4  g6  17.c4  Ne7  ∓  After 6... e5, White scores horribly in over-the-board play: 10/32 according to Mega Database 2018. This not only has to do with the objective assessment of the position  (which is probably =+)  , but also with the fact that Whites position is very unnatural and difficult to play. In my own games with 6... e5, I usually managed to reach winning positions quite quickly; here is one example:   7.Be2  My opponent was surprised by 6... e5 and produced this strange novelty. The bishop is placed passively on e2.  Nf6   the typical  7...Nc6 !  was slightly stronger  8.Bg5  the ending after   8.dxe5  Qxd1+  9.Bxd1  Nd5  is difficult for White and certainly not what a gambit player wants !  8...exd4  9.cxd4  Nc6  This is not a theoretically important line, so I will just show the moves of the game.  10.c3  h6  11.Bf4  Nd5  12.Qd2  Qe7  13.Kf2  Bf5  14.g3  Na5  White is not only a pawn down, but also under attack from all sides !  15.Qb2  O-O-O  16.Qb5  Nc6  17.Bc4  e3+  18.Kg2  a6  19.Qb2  g5  Now it is obvious that White loses decisive material.  20.Bxd5  Rxd5  21.c4  Rdd8  22.g4  gxf4  23.gxf5  Nxd4  0-1 Doehn-Langrock, Kassel 2003.  After   7.Qe2  Black has the choice between two promising continuations:  exd4   7...Nc6  8.dxe5   8.Bb2  Bf5  9.dxe5  Nh6  10.Rd1  Qh4+ !  Provoking White to weaken his light-squares.  11.g3  Qe7  12.fxe4  Bg4  13.Nf3  Nxe5  14.Bg2  O-O  15.O-O  f5  16.Qb5  Nxf3+  17.Bxf3  fxe4  18.Bxg4  Nxg4  ∓  Beutel-Leisebein, corr 2001  8...Nge7  is =+ according to Watson, who gives the sample line  9.Qxe4  Bf5  10.Qe2  Qd5  11.f4  O-O-O  8.Qxe4+  Qe7 ?  has been played in three correspondence games.  Instead, much more logical is Watsons suggestion,   8...Ne7  9.Qxd4  O-O  Black is ahead in development and has the better pawn structure. This cannot be fully compensated by Whites pair of bishops. }
7... Nc6
{ This looks most ambitious.   7...exd4  is a safe choice, although it releases the tension somewhat early.  8.Qxd4  Nf6   8...Qxd4 !?  9.Bxd4  Nf6  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.fxe4  led to a slightly better endgame for Black in Von ZitzewitzElburg, corr 1999. Black now has his own pawn weaknesses as well, but still the overall better structure.  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  10.O-O-O+  Black has kept his extra pawn, but with the two bishops and a slight initiative, White should be able to draw. The game Rodriguez-Haag, corr 2010, concluded  Nbd7  11.Bd4  Ke7  12.fxe4  c5  13.Bf2  Nxe4  14.Re1  f5  15.Bd3  Kf7  16.Bxe4  fxe4  17.Ne2  b6  18.Ng3  Bb7  19.Nxe4  Bxe4  20.Rxe4  Nf6  21.Rf4  g5  22.Rf3  Kg6  23.Rf1  Rhf8  24.Bg3  h5  25.Bd6  Rf7  -. }
8. dxe5
{ White has won his pawn back, but he ends up in a positionally worse position. A scenario, which is quite typical of the 6... e5-line.  Even worse is   8.d5  Na5  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.Bxd7+  Qxd7  11.fxe4  Qa4 !  ∓  12.Qg4  Nc4  13.Qxg7 ?  Nxe3  14.Qxh8  O-O-O  and Black wins. }
8... Qh4+ 9. g3
{ 9.Bf2  Qg5  10.Qe2  Qxe5  11.Qxe4  Qxe4+  12.fxe4  Nf6  13.Bd3  O-O  14.Ne2  Re8  15.Ng3  Ng4  16.h3  Nxf2  17.Kxf2  Ne5  Black was obviously better in Hanison-Killer, corr 2001. }
9... Qh5 10. f4
{ 10.Bd4  exf3  But not   10...Nxe5 ??  11.f4  and Black loses material because of the weakness of the g7-pawn.  11.Nxf3  Nge7  =+ }
10... Bg4
{ Black has chances on the light squares and the better pawn structure. This adds up to a considerable advantage. }
11. Qd5 Bf3 12. Qb5 Ne7 13. Be2 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Qg6 15. Rd1 Qe6 16. Bd2 f5 17. g4
{ This pseudo-aggressive move does not have many positive effects for White; in fact Black now gets the superb f5-square. }
17... fxg4
{ Good enough, although even stronger was   17...O-O-O !  finishing development and not even giving up the e4-pawn   18.gxf5  Qxf5  . }
18. Qxe4 O-O-O 19. Ne2 Nf5
{ Blacks positional advantage is obvious. He went on to win in 41 moves. } *

