1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@A safe move, but it generates an enthusiasm that I find mystifying. Apparently the French Defense is so powerful that White is happy to allow early equality. @@StartBracket@@ Watson @@EndBracket@@@@EndBlockQuote@@From a 2018 perspective it seems that the move 3. Bd3 has come here to stay. Several grandmasters have used it as a surprise weapon, while the strong Ukrainian GM Vladimir Onischuk has even played it quite regularly in the last years. Still, Black has different ways to equalize. I will show only one of them, but if you are interested in more, I can recommended Georgios Souleidis article in ChessBase Magazine 178. He discusses 3. Bd3 as a surprise weapon against the French for White, but is very objective and honest about the several ways Black can get an equal position. }
3... dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
