{ White was back in business and the game ended in a draw after 53 moves. Summary The last chapter of this book has shown how to proceed if White chooses one of the sidelines against the French Defense. As usual in a sideline chapter, some more or less obscure gambits had to be investigated. 3. Be3 ?! dxe4 4. Nd2 Nf6 5. f3 ?! is some sort of Blackmar-DiemerGambit with a passively placed knight on d2. After 5... Nd5 ! 6. Qe2 Nc6 7. c3 exf3 8. Ngxf3 Bd6 White maybe has the somewhat freer position, but as game 67 demonstrated, this is not enough to compensate for the lost pawn. While working on this book, I was surprised to find out how bad the natural-looking gambit 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. f3 ? is. The problem is that Black does not have to take on f3, but has a much better way to keep the extra pawn with 4... Bb4 !. I no longer think that White can equalize; see games 68 and 69. A much more sound choice is the Wing Gambit 2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 c5 4. b4. Todays strongest engines respect it, in the sense that they do not think that White is more than marginally worse if Black takes the pawn. This is no proof at all, but an indicator that White can count on reasonable long-term positional compensation after 4... cxb4 5. a3. If your opponent plays a bad gambit, you should take the pawn. Against sounder gambits like the Sicilian Morra or the French Wing Gambit, declining the offer is a good option. And as the motto of this book is to keep things solid, I decided to recommend the move 4... c4, which is a sound way to decline the gambit. One of the key ideas is to meet 5. c3 with 5... a5 !, fighting for the c5-square, and after 6. b5 Nd7 7. d3 cxd3 8. Bxd3 f6 ! Black can be optimistic as was illustrated in game 65. The move 2. b3 can also become a gambit after 2... d5 3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 f5, but here my recommendation is to follow the main line 4... Sf6 ! 5. Qe2 Be7 and not hold on to the extra pawn. Black should not forget to play actively as in many lines positions with opposite castling can arise. But if he does that, he is at least not worse as was shown in the games 63 and 64. Finally, there is the Two Knights Variation, 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3, and the modern line 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3. The former I recommended to meet in Rubinsteinesque fashion with 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7, which is rock-solid as could be seen in game 66. The latter is well answered by 3... dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5  (games 70 and 71)  . One point is that after 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4, Black has 8... Ne5 !, after which Whites bishop on f3 suddenly no longer looks that strong. }
